title: Generalized Linear Models in 3D
text: multiple linear regression creates flat regression surface. multiple linear regression interaction term can depicted curved regression surface linear marginal effects. generalized linear model (glm) takes linear component variable nonlinear function, creating curved regression surface nonlinear marginal effects. vignette demonstrates binomial model Gamma model. time, regress3d tested binomial models, negative binomials, Gammas, work generalized linear models. Interaction terms also allowed graphics generalized linear regressions. function add_jitter() demonstrated example binomial glm.

title: Generalized Linear Models in 3D
text: package regress3d built syntax plotly R. libraries called initial setup.
code: library(regress3d) library(plotly)

title: Generalized Linear Models in 3D
text: variables regression county level measures 2016. pedagogical purposes, variables chosen emphasize s-shape logistic regression. plurality_Trump16: binary variable indicating whether plurality county voted Trump 2016. any_college: percent adults county ever enrolled college, regardless whether graduated. prcnt_black: percent county identified Black 2016 census. purpose example regression weighted pop_estimate16. using weights, regression produces 0 1 estimates.

title: Generalized Linear Models in 3D
text: reference, two dimensional plot logistic regression can look like . outcome variable, plurality_Trump16, binary. use ggplot2::geom_jitter() reveal density observations counties Black residents. case, explanatory variable, prcnt_black, continuous. logistic regression model specified require s-shape predicted probabilities exceed range (0,1)(0,1).
code: county_data %>%   ggplot(aes(x = prcnt_black, y = plurality_Trump16)) +   geom_jitter(width = 0, height = 0.1, alpha = 0.5) +    geom_smooth(method = "glm", method.args = list(family = "binomial")) +   theme_classic()

title: Generalized Linear Models in 3D
text: three dimensional plot adds education logistic regression.
code: # county_data$frac_gop16 <- county_data$prcnt_GOP16/100   mymodel <- glm(plurality_Trump16 ~ any_college+prcnt_black,                 data = county_data,                 family = "binomial")  plot_ly( data = county_data,                         x = ~any_college,                         y = ~prcnt_black,                         z = ~plurality_Trump16) %>%   add_jitter(, x_jitter = 0, y_jitter = 0, z_jitter = 0.1,              size = 1, color = I('black'))%>%   add_3d_surface(model = mymodel, ci = T) %>%   add_marginals(model = mymodel, ci = T)

title: Generalized Linear Models in 3D
code: county_data %>%   ggplot(aes(x = median_income16)) +   geom_histogram() mymodel <- glm(median_income16 ~ prcnt_black +any_college,                 data = county_data, weight = pop_estimate16, family = Gamma)  p <- plot_ly( data = county_data,               x = ~prcnt_black,               y = ~any_college,               z = ~median_income16) %>%   add_markers(size = ~pop_estimate16, color = I('black')) %>%   add_3d_surface(model = mymodel)%>%   add_marginals(model = mymodel)   p

title: Linear Regression Surfaces with Marginal Effects in 3D
text: variables example county level demographic voting measures 2016. r_shift: shift towards Donald Trump 2016, measured difference county’s vote Trump 2016 county’s vote Republican presidential nominee, Mitt Romney, 2012, median_income16: median income, any_college: percent county enrolled college point, regardless whether graduated. regression weighted pop_estimate16, number people county, capture influence large counties.

title: Linear Regression Surfaces with Marginal Effects in 3D
text: code starts specifying model. create plotly::plot_ly() object using variables layer scattercloud, 3D surface, marginals, labels. Note regression notation uses x1x_1 x2x_2 represent explanatory variables, yy outcome. plotly command denotes explanatory variables xx yy, outcome variable zz. Click drag graphic rotate . needed, can reset image starting point. Hover image click house symbol top right graphic title. Alternately, can reload page. regression surface created predicted values model. shown flat dark blue surface. gray curved surfaces regression surface represent 95% confidence intervals. marginal effects corresponding confidence intervals shown red orange lines. Remove marginal effect clicking marginal effect legend. Return clicking marginal effect . Isolate marginal effect remove layers double clicking marginal effect legend. Double click return layers.
code: mymodel <- lm(r_shift ~ median_income16 + any_college,                data = county_data, weight = pop_estimate16)  plot_ly( data = county_data,          x = ~median_income16,          y = ~any_college,          z = ~r_shift) %>%   add_3d_surface(model = mymodel)%>%   add_marginals(model = mymodel)

what: Improvements with plotly, scales, and regress3d
title: Linear Regression Surfaces with Marginal Effects in 3D
text: can make interactive image prettier adding scatterpoints plotly function add_markers(), hovertemplate point, better labels. library scales helps present numeric values, percentages, dollars clearly. regress3d lets us modify legend text changing x1_direction_name x2_direction_name. default “Predicted marginal effect x1”. possible, shown , adjust value x2x_2 (x1x_1) held constant . See vignette interaction terms example.
code:
library(scales) plot_ly( data = county_data, x = ~median_income16, y = ~any_college, z = ~r_shift) %>% add_markers(size = ~pop_estimate16, hovertemplate = ~paste("", county_state,"
", "County population: ",comma(pop_estimate16),"

", "County median income: ",dollar(median_income16),"
", "County college experience: ",percent(any_college, accuracy = 0.1, scale = 1),"
", "Shift to Trump: ",percent(r_shift, accuracy = 0.01, scale = 1),"
"), showlegend = F, name = "county", color = I("black")) %>% add_3d_surface(model = mymodel) %>% add_marginals(model = mymodel, x1_direction_name = "Marginal effect of
county median income", x2_direction_name = "Marginal effect of
county college experience") %>% layout( title = "\nCounty shift to Trump in 2016", scene = list(xaxis = list(title = 'County median income'), yaxis = list(title = 'County college experience'), zaxis = list(title = 'Shift to Trump')), legend = list(font = list(size = 8)) )

text: package regress3d built syntax plotly R. libraries called initial setup.

title: Interaction Terms in 3D
text: interaction term linear regression can depicted curved regression surface linear marginal effects. marginal effects x1x_1 (x2x_2) allowed linearly change x2x_2 (x1x_1) changes. captures heterogenous effects regression, effect x1x_1 different different values x2x_2. Note change effect x1x_1 x2x_2 changes restricted linearity interaction term. equation predicted values linear regression two xx variables interaction term . ŷ=β̂1x1+β̂2x2+β̂12x1x2+β̂0\begin{align*} \hat{y} =& \hat{\beta}_1 x_1 +\hat{\beta}_2 x_2 +\hat{\beta}_{12} x_1 x_2 +  \hat{\beta}_0  \end{align*}

title: Interaction Terms in 3D
text: variables example county level demographic voting measures 2016. prcnt_GOP16: percent county’s voters voted Trump 2016, prcnt_unemployed: percent county unemployed 2016, college_2cat_num: binary measure county college experience. 0 county median value adult residents enrolled college point regardless whether graduated, 1 otherwise. regression weighted pop_estimate16, number people county, capture influence large counties.

title: Interaction Terms in 3D
code: county_data$prcnt_unemployed_log <- log(county_data$prcnt_unemployed)  mymodel <- lm(prcnt_GOP16~ prcnt_unemployed_log * college_2cat_num,                data = county_data, weights = pop_estimate16)  plot_ly( data = county_data,          x = ~prcnt_unemployed_log,          y = ~college_2cat_num,          z = ~prcnt_GOP16) %>%   add_3d_surface(model = mymodel)%>%   add_marginals(model = mymodel, x1_constant_val = 2.5, x2_constant_val =0)%>%   add_marginals(model = mymodel, x1_constant_val = 1, x2_constant_val =1)

title: Interaction Terms in 3D
code:
library(scales) county_data$prcnt_unemployed_log <- log(county_data$prcnt_unemployed) mymodel <- lm(prcnt_GOP16~ prcnt_unemployed_log * college_2cat_num, data = county_data, weights = pop_estimate16) plot_ly(data = county_data, x = ~prcnt_unemployed_log, y = ~college_2cat_num, z = ~prcnt_GOP16 ) %>% add_markers(size = ~pop_estimate16, hovertemplate = ~paste("", county_state,"
", "County population: ",comma(pop_estimate16), "

", "County unemployment: ", prcnt_unemployed,"
", "County college experience: ", percent(any_college, accuracy = 0.1, scale = 1),"
", "Trump Vote %: ", percent(prcnt_GOP16, accuracy = 0.01, scale = 1),"
"), showlegend = F, name = "county", color = ~college_2cat, colors = c("deepskyblue", "dimgrey")) %>% add_3d_surface(model = mymodel)%>% add_marginals(model = mymodel, x1_constant_val = 2.5, x2_constant_val =0)%>% add_marginals(model = mymodel, x1_constant_val = 1, x2_constant_val =1) %>% layout( title = "\nCounty Vote for Trump by\n unemployment & education", scene = list(xaxis = list(title = 'unemployment'), yaxis = list(title = 'education'), zaxis = list(title = '% vote for Trump 2016')), # width = 500, height = 500, legend = list(font = list(size = 8)) )

title: Create 3D Regression Surfaces
text: Next, create plotly::plot_ly() object using variables layer scattercloud, 3D surface, marginals, labels. Note regression notation uses x1x_1 x2x_2 represent explanatory variables, yy outcome. plotly command denotes explanatory variables xx yy, outcome variable zz. code renders html figure. displays outputs : add_3d_surface(): regression surface translucent blue, 95% confidence intervals translucent grey; add_marginals(): marginal effects 95% confidence intervals xx variable red orange lines; plotly::add_markers(): plotly function create scattercloud county used generate regression surface; plotly::layout(): plotly function adjust graphic’s labels. landing page package support interactive html figures. gif interactive html figure displayed demonstrate functionality interactive html image. See https://ellafostermolina.github.io/regress3d/articles/linear_models_3d.html#improvements--plotly interactive version image.  graphic corresponds following numerical regression results.
code: plot_ly( data = county_data,          x = ~median_income16,          y = ~any_college,          z = ~r_shift) %>%   add_markers(size = ~pop_estimate16, color = I("black"))  %>%   add_3d_surface(model = mymodel) %>%   add_marginals(model = mymodel) %>%   layout(      scene = list(xaxis = list(title = 'County median income'),                  yaxis = list(title = 'County college experience'),                  zaxis = list(title = 'Shift to Trump'))     )
